          <p id="IOM.CASEE.4">IOM was established in 1951, as the Intergovernmental Committee for Migration. Its predominantly operational humanitarian mandate included the handling of or­derly and planned migration, international resettlement, and facilitating the voluntary return and reintegration of migrants, refugees and internally displaced persons. The Committee's name was changed to IOM in 1989. IOM was admitted as an observer to the UN General Assembly in 1992. In June 2016 the IOM Council agreed that IOM should be incorporated into the UN system as a related organization; the new relationship was formalized at a UN Summit on Addressing Large Movements of Refugees and Migrants, held in September.</p>
          <int-org-section id="IOM.CASEE.135" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Members</heading>
               <p>There are 175 member states and eight observer member states. In addition, 78 international, governmental and non-governmental organizations hold observer status with IOM.</p>
          </int-org-section>
